'''Barry L. Frankhauser''' is an [[archaeologist]] who has worked in [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]].

==Works==
Frankhauser's Ph.D. thesis (published 1986) was a study of historical uses of the [[Cabbage tree (Cordyline australis)|cabbage tree]], an important food and fibre source in the [[Māori culture]] for at least 800 years.  The [[Māori Television]] network produced a [[Television documentary|TV documentary]] on the subject, using his thesis as a starting point, which aired in 2004. The documentary includes an interview with Frankhauser.

In 1990 Frankhauser participated in a two-day seminar (''Geochemical Methods for Dating of Rock Art'') held in [[Canberra]], which drew archeologists from three continents to evaluate the scientific soundness of the cation-ratio method of dating ancient rock art specimens.  That seminar concluded that the method had significant drawbacks and should be re-evaluated as a definitive test.<ref>http://www.uvm.edu/cosmolab/papers/Bednarik_1990_560.pdf{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Robert G. Bednarik, author</ref>

