[[File:Elf-Arrows.JPG|thumb|right|"Elf arrows" set in silver]] '''Elf-arrows''' or, in [[English folklore]], '''pixie arrows''',<ref>Carrington, C. E. & Jackson, J. Hampden. "[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ods8AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA2&lpg=PA2&dq=pixy-arrows&source=bl&ots=WMrYwtFAh6&sig=3yygs4WHNrNCM4UhWk7K_3jlOnA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiMkozC0ovKAhUDuhQKHTcvAcIQ6AEIKDAC#v=onepage&q=pixy-arrows&f=false A History of England]" CUP Archive, 1919. p. 3</ref> were [[arrowhead]]s of [[flint]] used in hunting and war by the [[Old Europe (archaeology)|Pre-Indo-European]] of the [[British Isles]] and of Europe generally, as they still are among native people elsewhere.{{cn|date=January 2017}} Elf-arrows derived their name from the [[folklore]] belief that the arrows fell from the sky, and were used by the [[elves]] to kill cattle and inflict [[elfshot]] on human beings.<ref>Merriam -Webster Dictionary: [http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/elf%20arrow Elf Arrow]</ref>
Elf-arrows were sometimes worn as [[amulet]]s, occasionally set in [[silver]], as a charm against [[witchcraft]].<ref>Electric Scotland. "Scottish Charms and Amulets" [http://www.electricscotland.com/history/articles/charms6.htm Elf-Arrows]</ref>
